                  <history>
                     <origin>
                        <origPlace>
                        <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1310Aksum">ʾAksum</placeName>
                     </origPlace> 
                         <origDate>c. 1400</origDate>
                     </origin>
                     <provenance>
                        The ms. was written in <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1310Aksum">Aksum</placeName> 
                        and presented by <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10803Yeshaq">Yǝsḥaq</persName> 
                        to the Ethiopian community in <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3957Jerusa">Jerusalem</placeName>. 
                        From there it passed to <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC5374Rome">Rome</placeName> 
                        together with other mss. and, having been transferred from the hostel of  <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0302SanStefano">San Stefano dei Mori</placeName> 
                        to the <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0307MB">Museo Borgiano</placeName>, 
                        it was stolen and brought to  <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC4325London">London</placeName>.
                        <p>In <date>1817</date> the bookseller <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10804Smith">J. Smith</persName> 
                           in Drury Lane sold it to Church Missionary Society, which transferred it to the <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0306BSL"> British and Foreign Bible Society</placeName>, for use in a printed Ethiopic edition. </p>
                           </provenance>
                  </history>
